After the Liberal International Order
Cambridge—Many analysts believe that the liberal international order ended with the rise of China and the election of U.S. President Donald Trump.
But if Joe Biden defeats Trump in the November election, should he try to revive it?
Perhaps the result is not so, but he must find some alternative.
Critics are correct in pointing out that the American order after 1945 was neither truly global nor always very liberal.
It excluded more than half of the world (including the Soviet bloc and China) and included many authoritarian states.
American hegemony has always been exaggerated.
Nevertheless, the most powerful country must take the lead in creating global public goods, otherwise they will not be provided — and Americans will also suffer as a result.
The current pandemic is a good example of this.
A realistic goal for the Biden administration should be to establish an international system based on rules, with different member states participating in handling different issues.
Would China and Russia be willing to participate?
In the 1990s and the 21st century, both countries were unable to balance American power, while the United States imposed its pursuit of liberal values above sovereignty.
The United States bombed Serbia and invaded Iraq without the approval of the UN Security Council.
It also supported a 2005 UN General Assembly resolution on "the responsibility to protect," aiming to protect citizens suffering from their own governments — which the United States later used as a justification for bombing Libya to protect citizens of Benghazi in 2011.
Critics describe this record as post-Cold War American hubris — for example, when the NATO-led intervention in Libya ultimately led to regime change, Russia and China felt deceived — while defenders of the operation describe it as the natural evolution of international humanitarian law.
No matter what, the growth of China's and Russia's power has more strictly restricted liberal interventionist actions.
So what remains?
Russia and China emphasize the principle of sovereignty stipulated in the UN Charter, which states that countries can only wage war for self-defense or with the approval of the Security Council.
Since 1945, it has been very rare for a country to occupy the territory of a neighboring country by force, and when it does happen, it will pay a high price in sanctions (as was the case with Russia's annexation of Crimea in 2014).
Furthermore, the Security Council often authorizes the deployment of peacekeeping forces in troubled countries, and political cooperation has successfully limited the proliferation of weapons of mass destruction and ballistic missiles.
This dimension of a rules-based order remains crucial.
Specifically in economic relations, the world needs to revise the rules.
Even before the pandemic, China's hybrid state capitalism supported an unfair mercantilist model, which distorted the functions of the World Trade Organization.
The result will lead to the decoupling of global supply chains, especially when national security is threatened.
Although China complains that the United States is preventing companies like Huawei from building 5G communication networks in the West, the United States' stance is consistent with sovereignty claims.
After all, China has blocked the operations of Google, Facebook, and Twitter in China for security reasons.
Negotiating new trade rules will help prevent the escalation of decoupling.
Meanwhile, despite the outbreak of this crisis, cooperation in key financial sectors remains very strong.
On the contrary, interdependence in the ecological field creates insurmountable obstacles in the face of sovereignty, as the threats are transnational.
No matter how much globalization in economics is hindered, environmental globalization will continue, as it obeys biological and physical laws, which contemporary geopolitical logic has no effect on.
The above issues threaten everyone, but no country is capable of solving them independently.
In issues such as the 2019 pandemic and climate change, power also has so-called positive-sum dimensions.
Under such premises, it is not enough to merely think about exercising power over others.
We must also think from the dimension of exercising power jointly with other countries.
The Paris Climate Agreement and the World Health Organization have been helpful to us and to others.
Since Nixon and Mao met in 1972, despite differences in the ideological field, this did not affect cooperation between China and the United States.
The dilemma Biden faces is whether China and the United States can cooperate in creating global public goods while engaging in competition in traditional great power domains.
The cyberspace is a new and important issue — because it partially has a transnational nature, but it is also controlled by sovereign governments.
The internet has already been partially fragmented.
Rules on internet freedom of speech and privacy can be established within democratic countries, but these rules will not be recognized by authoritarian countries.
As suggested by the Global Commission on the Stability of Cyberspace, if authoritarian regimes also want to achieve interconnectivity, certain rules that prohibit tampering with the fundamental structure of the internet would also be in their interest.
However, when they use proxies to conduct information warfare or interfere in elections (practices that infringe upon sovereignty), norms must be reinforced through rules such as those negotiated during the Cold War between the United States and the Soviet Union to limit the escalation of maritime incidents (even though hostility in the ideological realm still exists).
The United States and like-minded countries must publicly state the norms they intend to uphold and establish the necessary deterrence.
Adhering to the values of freedom in cyberspace does not mean the United States unilaterally disarms.
On the contrary, the United States should distinguish between permissible soft power such as open persuasion and hard power such as covert information warfare, and it will certainly retaliate when the other side launches covert information warfare.
It is permissible to allow Russia and China to broadcast programs and radio openly, but secret unifying actions such as manipulating social media are not allowed.
Moreover, the United States will continue to criticize the human rights records of these countries.
Public opinion polls show that the American public wants to avoid military intervention, but does not want to withdraw from alliances or multilateral cooperation.
Moreover, the public still values these values.
If Biden is elected, the issue he faces is not whether to restore the liberal international order.
The issue is whether the United States can cooperate with its core allies to promote democracy and human rights, while simultaneously cooperating with a broader range of countries to manage the rules-based international institutions needed to address transnational threats such as climate change, pandemics, cyberattacks, terrorism, and economic turmoil.
